summary: I was astounded (and pretty skeptical) when I saw articles saying Study says Trained Dogs Can Identify COVID-19 and Researchers successfully train dogs to detect COVID-19 infections. Alarm bells for fake news were ringing in my head. Had curiosity not got the better of me, I would have disregarded the headlines as another attempt from unreliable sources to advertise dishonest science and beguile to the unassuming reader. But upon further inspection, I found I was completely wrong…and I’m glad I was!
title: Study finds man's best friend may have a role to play in testing for COVID-19

summary:
“How many roads must a man walk down
Before you call him a man?
How many seas must a white dove sail
Before she sleeps in the sand?
Yes, and how many times must the cannon balls fly
Before they’re forever banned?
The answer, my friend, is blowin’ in the wind
The answer is blowin’ in the wind.”
Recognize those lines? Bob Dylan, one of America’s greatest songwriters, wrote Blowin’ in the Wind in 1962, to illustrate that some of life’s answers are as biting and as difficult to grasp as the wind itself.
title: NLP on American Songwriting

html: Using hypothetical data to explore a common statistical test in medicine
summary:
Fisher’s exact test is a common statistical test implemented for count data in a contingency table. The name gets the term exact from the fact that the test compares group counts to the hypergeometric function and thus returns an exact probability of obtaining counts of different outcomes.
As an example, let’s consider a hypothetical study of mice evenly split into two groups– a control group and a treatment group. The treated mice will receive a vaccine before infection while the control group will not.
title: Fisher’s Exact Test

Looking into datahub’s Liverpool match data, I was able to investigate trends for goals scored by and against the Reds from 2009 up to last year’s EPL season. Boxplots below show this data over the ten year period.
 The number of goals are pretty variable, and with only 38 games per season, sample size is fairly low. I wanted to use Bayesian statistics to estimate goals for and against Liverpool based on these yearly samples.
title: Liverpool Goal Trends

summary: R Package Development for Survival Analysis For those that don’t know, the NIH (National Institutes of Health) is made up of 27 institutes and centers. One of those centers, the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Dieseases (NIAID), has a special program designed to bring data scientists within the institute to gain hands-on-experience in applying and managing big data, bioinformatics strategies, and software development. NIAID’s mission is to conduct and support basic and applied research to better understand, treat, and ultimately prevent infectious, immunologic, and allergic diseases.

I love NCAA March Madness. Although I never really watch college basketball through the regular season, I find the tournament too thrilling to ignore. Given that I have no understanding of most of the teams when the tourney starts, I have to rely on data and modeling techniques to make some sort of educated guesses.

html: A confidence interval simulator showing imperfections between theoretical and empirical type 1 error rates
summary:
https://webb-kyle.shinyapps.io/shinyapp-confidence-int/
This shiny app calculates confidence intervals from normal distributions with subsampling criteria specified by the user. Number of confidence intervals (Samples) is also defined by the user as well as the mean and standard deviation of the distribution. Note the discrepencies between empirical and theoretical error rates. These are pronounced when subsampling numbers are low. This example demonstrates one of the pitfalls with frequentist statistics and a reliance upon confidence interval estimation.
title: Confidence Interval

summary:
https://webb-kyle.shinyapps.io/mixture_simulation/
Here’s the link for the first shiny app I ever built. Basically, this simulator lets the user select the number of components (Normal distributions) they want to randomly sample from. The mean and standard deviation of the distributions are randomly assigned and the sample sizes for the distributions are user-selected as 200, 500, 1000, 2000, or 5000 points from each component. Mu (mean) and Dev (standard deviation) results will show in a resulting table.
title: My first shiny app
